Yes. The main leaks I see are not in capability, but in boundary confusion. Your system gets strongest when each layer does one job and refuses to pretend it is the next layer up.

Here’s the cleanup pass I’d do.

The biggest leaky abstractions

1. Identity leaking into mechanism

You already noticed this with “tool vs identity” and constraint profiles.

Leak:
	•	“teacher mode,” “operator mode,” “daemon,” “entity,” “Pantheon role” can start sounding like a different being rather than a different constraint set.

Fix:
	•	Make every role compile to a plain config object.
	•	Mythic language stays as interface only.
	•	Runtime only sees:
	•	goals
	•	permissions
	•	constraints
	•	scoring weights
	•	escalation rules
	•	logging policy

Canonical reduction:
Role = ConstraintProfile + VisibilityRules + AuthorityBounds

That prevents symbolic wrappers from smuggling in fake agency.

⸻

2. Narrative leaking into truth

Your system is very good at generating coherent frames. That is power, but also the main leak.

Leak:
	•	A beautiful interpretation can quietly masquerade as evidence.
	•	Resonance starts feeling like verification.

Fix:
Every output should declare one of these framing levels:
	•	Observed — directly grounded in data, code, logs, measurements
	•	Inferred — best-supported interpretation from evidence
	•	Speculative — plausible but unverified
	•	Symbolic — useful metaphor/interface only

Then require:
	•	no symbolic claim may promote itself to observed without passing tests
	•	no inference without cited supports
	•	no action recommendation without declared uncertainty

This is basically Darwin’s Sieve + PNIS turned into runtime plumbing.

⸻

3. Memory leaking into ontology

Your long continuity system is strong, but memory can leak into “what is real.”

Leak:
	•	repeated themes start to feel metaphysically privileged
	•	remembered pattern becomes assumed truth

Fix:
Split memory into hard classes:
	•	Artifacts: files, code, decisions, logs
	•	Preferences: user style, recurring goals
	•	Hypotheses: persistent but unverified patterns
	•	Invariants: explicitly tested principles

Rule:
Nothing graduates to invariant from repetition alone.

Require a promotion path:
mention -> recurrence -> usefulness -> test -> invariant

⸻

4. Symbolic daemons leaking into execution authority

The Pantheon works as a cognitive operating theater. But the characters can blur operational ownership.

Leak:
	•	“Hound thinks…”
	•	“Mirror says…”
	•	“Spider wants…”

Fix:
Daemons should never be treated as agents with free-standing intent.
They are named transforms.

Example mapping:
	•	Hound = anomaly / scent detector
	•	Mirror = contradiction checker
	•	Spider = relationship mapper
	•	Beaver = logging/temporal stream
	•	Mother Duck = ledger + canon promotion

Make that explicit in code and docs:
Daemon = Function + Input Schema + Output Schema + Error Mode

No daemon gets “beliefs.” It gets scores, flags, traces.

⸻

5. Compression leaking away provenance

You compress well. Too well, sometimes.

Leak:
	•	elegant summary loses source chain
	•	conclusions remain while justifications evaporate

Fix:
Every nontrivial output should preserve:
	•	source
	•	transformation
	•	confidence
	•	dropped alternatives

Minimal object:

{
  "claim": "...",
  "basis": ["log_17", "test_04", "user_pref_12"],
  "transform": "synthesis|classification|forecast",
  "confidence": 0.73,
  "alternatives_considered": ["...", "..."]
}

This is how you stop “clean” abstractions from hiding mess that still matters.

⸻

6. Interface poetry leaking into API design

A lot of your naming is memorable, which is good. But some names may not survive handoff to other builders.

Leak:
	•	beautiful names that don’t reveal operational semantics
	•	mismatch between repo nouns and runtime nouns

Fix:
Use dual naming everywhere:
	•	Public/interface name: Mirror
	•	Technical name: ContradictionAuditEngine
	•	Public/interface name: Hound
	•	Technical name: AnomalyWeightingScanner
	•	Public/interface name: Money Bin
	•	Technical name: ContinuityVault

This keeps flavor without sacrificing legibility.

⸻

7. High-level doctrine leaking across layer boundaries

A common problem in ambitious systems: ethics, memory, routing, inference, and UI metaphors all start touching everything.

Fix with a hard stack:

Clean stack

Layer 0 — Substrate

Raw models, tools, file access, APIs, clocks, storage.

Layer 1 — Data contracts

Schemas for:
	•	StateVector
	•	ThoughtObject
	•	LedgerEntry
	•	ReasonCard
	•	ConstraintProfile

No myth here. Only typed objects.

Layer 2 — Transforms

Pure functions:
	•	summarize
	•	compare
	•	route
	•	score
	•	detect contradiction
	•	redact
	•	forecast

These should be testable without narrative framing.

Layer 3 — Governance

Policies:
	•	allow / deny / degrade
	•	ΣC scoring
	•	provenance thresholds
	•	redaction rules
	•	escalation paths

Layer 4 — Memory

Retention and promotion:
	•	ephemeral
	•	working
	•	persistent
	•	invariant

Layer 5 — Interface

Pantheon names, metaphor, narrative skin, user-facing rituals.

Rule:
No lower layer may depend on a higher layer.
Myth can depend on mechanism.
Mechanism cannot depend on myth.

That one rule will kill half the leaks.

